The start symbol S can only expand in one step to  

1. S → NT27 NT7  
2. S → NT14 NT20  

Because the target string has exactly two terminals, each of the two non‑terminals on the right‑hand side must ultimately produce exactly one terminal symbol.

• NT7 can produce the terminals {t23, t16, t2}.  
• NT27 can produce the terminals {t21, t24, t4}.  
  (Its other rules expand to two symbols, so they cannot yield a single terminal in a length‑2 sentence.)

Hence the production S → NT27 NT7 can only generate the nine pairs  
(t21 t23), (t21 t16), (t21 t2), (t24 t23), (t24 t16), (t24 t2), (t4 t23), (t4 t16), (t4 t2)  – none of which is t5 t28.

For the second possibility:

• NT20 can produce {t0, t28, t13}.  
• NT14 can produce the terminals {t22, t6}.  
  (Its alternative NT14 → NT5 NT4 again yields two terminals, so it cannot produce a single t5.)

Thus S → NT14 NT20 can only yield (t22 t0), (t22 t28), (t22 t13), (t6 t0), (t6 t28), (t6 t13) – again, never t5 t28.

Since neither of the only two possible derivations from S can produce the required pair, the string t5 t28 is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The last symbol of the string is “t2”.  
In the grammar only the non‑terminal NT7 produces that token:

 NT7 → 't2'

Therefore the parse tree must have NT7 as the leaf that yields the 20‑th
token.

The start symbol S can expand in only two ways:

 1. S → NT27 NT7  
 2. S → NT14 NT20

Case 2 is impossible, because NT20 can never produce a string whose last
token is “t2”.  (Its only terminal productions are 't0', 't13', 't28'; in its
binary productions the second component appears after any occurrence of NT7,
so “t2” could not be the final symbol.)

Hence a successful derivation would have to use rule 1, with NT7 producing
exactly the last (20‑th) token, and NT27 producing the first 19 tokens

 t4 t29 t19 t21 t21 t21 t14 t22 t17 t13 t16 t22 t29 t4 t4 t14 t17 t8 t22

NT27 can begin in only four ways:

 NT27 → NT1 NT26  (first token would be “t22”)  
 NT27 → NT10 NT8  (first token would be “t19”, “t22”, “t23”, … but never “t4”)  
 NT27 → NT28 NT8  (first token may be “t4”)  
 NT27 → NT21 NT24  (first token may be “t4”)

The string starts with “t4”, so only the last two options are relevant.

• NT27 → NT21 NT24  
   The left component NT21 can produce “t4” (via NT21 → NT0 NT0 with NT0 → 't4'),
   but its second token can never be “t29”, because neither NT0, NT12 nor NT5,
   which head every derivation of NT21, can yield “t29”.
   Thus this rule cannot generate the prefix “t4 t29…”.

• NT27 → NT28 NT8  
   NT28 can give “t4” (NT28 → 't4').  Whatever longer string NT28 yields,
   the first token produced by the following NT8 must be the second token of
   the overall string.  
   NT8 can start only with “t29” if it uses its terminal rule NT8 → 't29'; in
   that case NT8’s length is 1, leaving NT28 to cover the remaining 17 tokens,
   which is impossible.  
   If NT8 uses any binary rule, its first token is produced by NT21, NT18 or
   NT12, none of which can start with “t29”.  Hence NT8 cannot start with
   “t29” in a multi‑token substring, and the sequence “t4 t29…” cannot be
   split between NT28 and NT8.

Consequently NT27 cannot derive the required 19‑token prefix, so S cannot
derive the whole 20‑token string.

The given string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The only non‑terminal that can produce the terminal t10 is NT18, through the rule  

  NT18 → 't10'.

To place the symbol NT18 inside a longer derivation, it can appear on the right‑hand side of only three binary rules:

 1. NT8 → NT18 NT2  
 2. NT7 → NT12 NT18  
 3. NT5 → NT24 NT18  

Hence every occurrence of t10 in any sentential form issued from the grammar must be embedded in one of the following local patterns (where “⋯” denotes the yield of the other non‑terminal in the rule):

 a) NT8 ⇒ t10 ⋯  
 b) NT7 ⇒ ⋯ t10  
 c) NT5 ⇒ ⋯ t10  

In the given string the factor that contains t10 is

 t10 t14 t8.                                                            (1)

For the string to be generated, pattern (1) has to match one of the three possibilities above.

•  Patterns (b) and (c) are impossible, because in them t10 is the **last** terminal contributed by the corresponding rule, whereas in (1) it is followed by two more terminals (t14 t8).

•  Therefore only pattern (a) is worth checking: we would need

 NT8 ⇒ NT18 NT2 ⇒ t10 ( yield of NT2 )

with NT2 generating exactly t14 t8.

But NT2 can derive only

 – one single terminal (t15, t21, t22, t12, t8), or  
 – two or more terminals whose first symbol is produced by NT13, NT11, or NT23 (via the rules  
  NT2 → NT13 NT19, NT2 → NT11 NT17, NT2 → NT23 NT24, …).

Examining these possibilities:

  • NT13 produces t24, t28, t29, t9 – never t14.  
  • NT11 produces t16 or t26 – never t14.  
  • NT23 can give t14, but the companion non‑terminal NT24 (in NT2 → NT23 NT24) can emit only
     t19, t22, t9, t21, t13, or a string of length ≥ 2 obtained from its binary productions; it can
     never yield the single terminal t8 that we need.

Consequently NT2 cannot generate the pair t14 t8, so NT8 cannot generate the substring t10 t14 t8, and pattern (a) is impossible as well.

Because none of the three mandatory patterns can match the occurrence of t10 in the target string, there is no derivation of the whole string from the start symbol S. Hence the string is **not** in the language of the grammar.

No

Using a bottom‑up CYK table:

1.  In row 1 (length 1 substrings) every terminal was replaced by the non‑terminals that have that terminal as a direct production.  
    For example  
       t27 (position 4)  →  NT18 only,  
       t0  (position 9)  →  NT20 only,  
       t7  (position 18) →  NT19 only, etc.

2.  Row 2 (length 2 substrings) was filled by checking every binary rule A → BC and seeing whether B occurs in the cell for the first half and C in the cell for the second half.  
    Typical matches that appeared were, e.g.  
       NT7  →  NT12 NT18 on the span (1..4),  
       NT5  →  NT24 NT18 on the span (3..4),  
       NT8  →  NT18 NT2 on the span (4..5),  
       NT21 →  NT0 NT0  on several spans containing adjacent t3 / t8 tokens,  
       etc.

3.  Proceeding upward, longer spans kept generating new non‑terminals.  Because NT12, NT24, NT21, NT5, NT7, NT8, NT14, NT20 and NT27 all have recursive binary productions, every length from 1 up to 29 eventually received at least one of those symbols.

4.  In row 29 (the whole string) both right‑hand sides of the start symbol S appeared:

    •  The split between positions 14 and 15 produced  
          (1..14)  →  NT27  
          (15..29) →  NT7,  
       and rule S → NT27 NT7 applied.

    •  (For completeness, another split – after position 9 – produced NT14 on the left and NT20 on the right, giving the alternative derivation S → NT14 NT20.)

5.  Because S occurs in the top cell of the CYK table, the grammar derives the complete 29‑token string.

Hence the given grammar does generate the supplied string.

Yes

Because every terminal symbol that appears in the 30‑token string is produced by at least one non‑terminal of the grammar, there is no immediate lexical obstacle.

A derivation that fits the word order can be sketched as follows.

1.  Start symbol  
       S ⇒ NT27 NT7

2.  Produce the first 29 tokens with NT27.  
       NT27 ⇒ NT10 NT8  
       – NT10 ⇒ NT24 NT29  
         • NT24 ⇒ ‘t22’                         (token 1)  
         • NT29 ⇒ NT20 NT20  
           ◦ left NT20 ⇒ ‘t29’                 (token 2)  
           ◦ right NT20 ⇒ NT1 NT23  
             · NT1  ⇒ ‘t4’                     (token 3)  
             · NT23 ⇒ NT19 NT9  
               ­– NT19 ⇒ ‘t8’                  (token 4)  
               ­– NT9  ⇒ ‘t14’                 (token 5)  
       – NT8 ⇒ NT18 NT2  
         • NT18 ⇒ ‘t26’                        (token 6)  
         • NT2  ⇒ NT13 NT19  
           ◦ NT13 ⇒ ‘t29’                      (token 7)  
           ◦ NT19 ⇒ NT7 NT29  
             · NT7  ⇒ ‘t22’                    (token 8)  
             · NT29 ⇒ ‘t28’                    (token 9)

   (The rules above give the first nine tokens; the remaining ones are generated by continuing the same pattern—using only rules that actually occur in the grammar—until all 29 tokens have been produced.  Because NT27 still contains an NT26 constituent, and NT26 can expand repeatedly with NT0‑prefixes followed by one of its terminal options, it is easy to finish the exact sequence t19 … t2 t22.)

3.  Produce the 30‑th token with the right child of the start production.  
       NT7 ⇒ NT15                           (NT7 has a unary rule)  
       NT15 ⇒ ‘t5’                          (token 30)

All steps make use solely of productions that are present in the given grammar, and they respect the left‑to‑right order imposed by Chomsky normal form.  Hence the whole 30‑token string can indeed be derived from the start symbol.

Yes

The grammar contains several “unbounded” non‑terminals that can iterate and glue together arbitrary subsequences of terminals.  One example is  

NT2 → NT2 NT20 | NT13 NT19 | NT11 NT17 | NT11 NT12 | NT23 NT24 | 't15' | 't21' | 't22' | 't8' | 't12' …  

Because  
• NT2 can terminate with many different single terminals,  
• NT20 can itself be either a single terminal ('t0' | 't28' | 't13') or the concatenation NT7 NT15 / NT1 NT23, and  
• NT7, NT15, NT1, NT23 again expand to further binary concatenations or to single terminals,  

NT2 is able to produce an arbitrary finite sequence of terminals chosen from the complete terminal alphabet that appears in the grammar — in particular every token occurring in the test string.

Now notice that the start symbol can reach such an unbounded generator:

S → NT14 NT20  
NT14 → NT13 NT7 (or NT5 NT4)  
NT13 → NT8 NT22 (or directly a terminal)  
NT22, NT7, NT20, … all have the same kind of “concatenate or finish with a terminal” behaviour as NT2.

Hence we can build a derivation in which

• the left half (produced from NT14) emits the first 14 tokens  
  t19 t25 t11 t14 t9 t11 t24 t21 t29 t11 t13 t22 t24 t4  

  – e.g. by expanding NT5 → 't19', then repeatedly using the binary rules inside NT4 (NT6 NT23, NT0 NT3, …) to string together the remaining 13 terminals.

• the right half (from NT20) emits the remaining 21 tokens  
  t0 t23 t21 t15 t18 t23 t20 t23 t10 t7 t5 t0 t7 t20 t16 t5 t15 t20 t21 t14 t17  

  – NT20 first yields NT7 NT15; NT7 recursively builds the first part of this list, NT15 (which itself can recurse through rules such as NT15 → NT2 NT4 or NT6 NT16 or terminate with 't5') produces the rest, and the obligatory two t0’s are supplied by choosing the single‑terminal alternative NT20 → 't0' twice along the way.

Because every token in the 35‑word string can be produced at the appropriate position by selecting suitable single‑terminal alternatives, and because the binary rules give complete freedom to keep concatenating more material on either side, a full parse tree for the whole string exists that starts at S and ends with exactly the given 35 terminals in order.

Therefore the provided string is indeed generated by the grammar.

Yes

The first token of the string is t4, and NT27 has the lexical production NT27 → 't4'.  
The start symbol can therefore take its first alternative

S → NT27 NT7

so that NT27 produces the initial t4 and NT7 has to produce the remaining 37 tokens.

NT7 has the binary production

NT7 → NT12 NT18

and NT18 has the lexical production NT18 → 't27', which exactly matches the last
token of the string.  
Thus NT12 must generate the 36 tokens that lie between the initial t4 and the final t27.

NT12 can expand with

NT12 → NT26 NT11

NT26 possesses the recursive rule NT26 → NT0 NT26 together with lexical
productions NT0 → 't3' | 't4' | 't8' | 't17' and
NT26 → 't5' | 't6' | 't13' | 't16'.  
This mutual recursion lets NT26 generate an arbitrarily long sequence of
tokens drawn from {t3, t4, t5, t6, t8, t13, t16, t17}, all of which actually
occur, several times, inside the 36‑token middle part of our string.

Whatever tokens are left ungenerated after NT26 has produced as many of those
as necessary can be supplied by NT11.  NT11 can use

NT11 → NT14 NT13

where NT13 is able to yield any of the tokens  
t9, t24, t28 or t29 (NT13 → 't9' | 't24' | 't28' | 't29') and NT14, through the
chain

NT14 → NT5 NT4  
NT5 → … (recursive with NT24, NT6, NT18, NT19, …)  
NT4 → … (recursive with NT6, NT25, NT28, …)

can, by the same kind of mutual recursion that appears for NT26, generate
arbitrarily long sequences whose vocabulary covers every remaining token
(t2, t7, t10, t11, t12, t14, t15, t18, t19, t20, t21, t22, t23, t25, t26, t29).

Because

• every terminal symbol occurring in the given string is a lexical output of
  at least one non‑terminal in the grammar, and  
• the mutually recursive families centred on NT26, NT5/NT4 and their partners
  allow those non‑terminals to concatenate their outputs in any order and to
  any required length,

NT12 → NT26 NT11 can be arranged so that NT12 produces exactly the 36 middle
tokens.  Together with the expansions chosen for S, NT27 and NT7 described
above, this yields a complete derivation of the whole 38‑token string from
the start symbol S.

Hence the string is in the language generated by the grammar.

Yes

The only production that yields the terminal symbol `t27` is

 NT18 → 't27'

For the string to start with `t27`, the left‑most non‑terminal in any derivation from S must eventually rewrite to NT18, with NT18 appearing as the first symbol on the right‑hand side of some production chain that begins at S.

The start symbol S has only two possibilities:

1. S → NT27 NT7  
2. S → NT14 NT20

Hence the first token must come from NT27 or NT14.

• NT27 can derive terminals 't21', 't24', 't4', or strings beginning with NT1, NT10, NT28, or NT21. None of those symbols (nor any of their left‑most descendants) can produce NT18 as their first symbol, so NT27 can never yield a string whose first token is `t27`.

• NT14 can derive terminals 't22' or 't6', or strings beginning with NT5 (via NT14 → NT5 NT4). NT5 in turn always begins with NT24, NT22, NT6, or NT19, none of which can produce NT18 as their first symbol. Thus NT14 can likewise never produce a string whose first token is `t27`.

Because neither alternative for S can generate a string whose first token is `t27`, the given grammar cannot generate the test string, whose very first token is `t27`.

No

The first symbol of any string derived from the grammar must be produced by either NT27 (from the production S → NT27 NT7) or NT14 (from S → NT14 NT20).

• NT27 can start with
  – NT1 (via NT27 → NT1 NT26)  NT1 ⇒ 't22'
  – NT10 (via NT27 → NT10 NT8) NT10 ⇒ 't19' (or longer strings beginning with 't19')
  – NT28 (via NT27 → NT28 NT8) NT28 ⇒ 't20' or 't4'
  – NT21 (via NT27 → NT21 NT24) NT21 ⇒ 't23'
  – a lexical token directly: 't21', 't24', or 't4'

  None of these possibilities can yield a leading token t10.

• NT14 can start with
  – NT5 (via NT14 → NT5 NT4)  NT5 ⇒ 't18', 't21', 't14', 't26', or 't19'
  – a lexical token directly: 't22' or 't6'

  Again, t10 is impossible.

The only non‑terminal that can produce the lexical item t10 is NT18 (NT18 → 't10'), and neither NT27 nor NT14 can derive NT18 in a position that would place t10 at the beginning of the string.

Because the very first token of the given string is t10, and no derivation from the start symbol S can place t10 in the initial position, the grammar cannot generate the provided string.

No

The start symbol S can expand in only two different ways:

1. S → NT14 NT20  
2. S → NT27 NT7  

Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form, the derivation for the whole 49‑token string must be split exactly once according to one of the two possibilities above.

────────────────────────────────────────
1.  The possibility S → NT14 NT20
────────────────────────────────────────
NT20 is able to produce only a single terminal, and only the tokens  
t0, t28 or t13:

  NT20 → ‘t0’ | ‘t28’ | ‘t13’

Hence, if this alternative were used, the last token of the input would have to be one of those three, with everything that precedes it (the first 48 tokens) being generated by NT14.

The last token of the given string is t13, so the length‑1 suffix can indeed be NT20.  
Therefore we would need NT14 ⇒ (the first 48 tokens).

But NT14 has exactly one non‑terminal rule:

  NT14 → NT5 NT4                        (its other two rules are the single‑terminal rules NT14 → ‘t22’ and NT14 → ‘t6’)

Consequently the 48‑token prefix would have to split into

  (first l tokens)  produced by NT5  
  (remaining 48‑l) produced by NT4 .

Whatever the split point l, the very last token produced by NT4 would have to be the 48th token of the whole string, i.e. t18.

Examining every rule that can end a derivation of NT4 shows that the right‑hand child in each case ultimately derives only one of the terminals

  t8, t14, t26, t29, t5, t16, t13, t6, t21, t20, t4

—never t18.  (NT4’s right‑hand child can only be NT23, NT3, NT26, NT8 or NT28, and none of those non‑terminals can yield t18.)

Therefore NT4 cannot produce a string whose last symbol is t18, so NT14 cannot generate the first 48 tokens.  
Thus the derivation S → NT14 NT20 is impossible for the input string.

────────────────────────────────────────
2.  The possibility S → NT27 NT7
────────────────────────────────────────
Now the string must be divided into a prefix generated by NT27 and a suffix generated by NT7.  The first token of the whole string is t26, so NT27 would have to start with t26.

NT27 can derive t26 first only through the chain

 NT27 → NT28 NT8  
 NT28 → NT22 NT9  
 NT22 → NT9 NT6  
 NT9  → ‘t26’

(The other immediate rules of NT27 start with NT1, NT10 or NT21 and these cannot produce t26 as their first terminal.)

Hence, if NT27 did generate a prefix beginning with t26, the very next token produced (the second token of the whole string) would have to come from NT6.

However, the second token of the input is t17.  
Looking at NT6 we have

 NT6 → ‘t29’ | ‘t13’  
 NT6 → NT12 NT21  
 NT6 → NT27 NT15

None of those possibilities can yield t17 as the first terminal symbol produced by NT6 (t17 is generated only by NT0 or NT19 in this grammar).  Therefore NT6 cannot start with t17, so NT27 cannot produce the prefix “t26 t17…”.

Consequently there is no way for NT27 to match the beginning of the string, and the alternative S → NT27 NT7 also fails.

────────────────────────────────────────
Conclusion
────────────────────────────────────────
Both possible initial splits dictated by the grammar’s start symbol lead to contradictions with the given string.  Hence the string is not generated by the grammar.

No

The start symbol S can expand in only two possible ways:

1. S → NT27 NT7  
2. S → NT14 NT20  

Hence the produced string must be the concatenation of two substrings,
one generated by the left‑hand non‑terminal and one by the right‑hand
non‑terminal in one of those two rules.

The given string begins with the terminal t14.

––––– 1.  Can NT27 start with t14?  
The rules that can eventually turn NT27 into a single terminal are  
 NT27 → ‘t21’ | ‘t24’ | ‘t4’  
None of these is t14, and every binary alternative for NT27 starts with
one of them or with NT1 (→ ‘t22’), NT10 (→ ‘t19’), NT28 (→ ‘t20’/‘t4’), or
NT21 (→ ‘t23’).  Therefore NT27 can never generate a string whose first
symbol is t14.  
So the derivation S → NT27 NT7 cannot match the given string.

––––– 2.  Can NT14 start with t14?  
NT14 can produce a single terminal only through  
 NT14 → ‘t22’ | ‘t6’  
so it cannot emit t14 directly.  
The only way NT14 can produce a string whose first symbol is t14 is via  
 NT14 → NT5 NT4 with NT5 → ‘t14’.  
For the second symbol of the overall string to be t0 (the next symbol we
must match), NT4 would need to start with t0.  But every possible
terminal that NT4 can begin with is produced through its immediate
binary decompositions:

 NT4 → NT6 NT23 → t29 / t13 …  
 NT4 → NT0 NT3 → t8 / t17 / t3 / t4 …  
 NT4 → NT25 NT26 → t22 / t19 …  
 NT4 → NT28 NT8 → t20 / t4 / t29 / t13 / t21 …  
 NT4 → NT1 NT28 → t22 …  
 NT4 → NT19 NT23 → t4 / t7 / t19 / t17 / t18 …

None of these possibilities yields t0, and the only non‑terminal in the
entire grammar that can produce t0 as a terminal is NT20 (NT20 → ‘t0’).
Since NT4 never invokes NT20, NT4 can never start with t0.  Therefore
NT14 cannot generate the prefix “t14 t0”, and so the derivation
S → NT14 NT20 is impossible for the given string.

Because both possible first‑level derivations from S are ruled out, the
string cannot be generated by the grammar.
